[Steve Carell]], that premiered on [[Apple TV+]] on November 1, 2019.<ref name=\"SeriesOrder\">{{Cite web |url=http://deadline.com/2017/11/apple-reese-witherspoon-jennifer-aniston-morning-show-series-2-season-order-amazing-stories-reboot-1202204293/ |title=Apple Gives Reese Witherspoon-Jennifer Aniston Morning Show Series 2-Season Order, Confirms \u2018Amazing Stories\u2019 Reboot |last=Andreeva |first=Nellie |date=November 8, 2017 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.instagram.com/p/Bvctd5nDE0F/ |title=Reese Witherspoon on Instagram: \"So excited to announce my new @apple show at the #appleevent! It\u2019s called The Morning Show \u2600\ufe0fand it reveals what happens in the fast-paced\u2026\" |website=Instagram |access-date=2019-04-30}}</ref> The series is inspired by [[Brian Stelter]]'s book ''[[Top of the Morning (book)|Top of the Morning: Inside the Cutthroat World of Morning TV]]''.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2017/nov/08/apple-tv-show-reese-witherspoon-jennifer-aniston |title=Apple announces drama series starring Reese Witherspoon and Jennifer Aniston |date=8 November 2017 |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=2 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Premise==\nAlex Levy anchors ''The Morning Show'', a popular [[Breakfast television|breakfast]] news program broadcast from [[New Yorkers in journalism|Manhattan]] on the UBA network that has excellent viewership ratings and is perceived to have changed the face of American television.\n\nAfter her on-air partner of 15 years, Mitch Kessler, is fired amidst a [[sexual misconduct]] scandal, Alex fights to retain her job as top news anchor while sparking a rivalry with Bradley Jackson, a haphazard [[Correspondent|field reporter]] whose series of impulsive decisions bring her into a new world of TV journalism.\n\n==Cast and characters==\n===Main===\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Jennifer Aniston]] as Alex Levy, co-host of UBA's ''The Morning Show''\n* [[Reese Witherspoon]] as Bradley Jackson, a field reporter turned ''TMS'' co-host\n* [[Steve Carell]] as Mitch Kessler, the recently-fired co-host of ''The Morning Show''\n* [[Billy Crudup]] as Cory Ellison,<ref name=\"MbathaRawCrudup\" /> a UBA executive from the network's entertainment division who recently took over news operations\n* [[Mark Duplass]] as Charlie \"Chip\" Black,<ref name=\"CarbonellDuplass\" /> the Executive Producer of ''The Morning Show''\n* [[Gugu Mbatha-Raw]] as Hannah Shoenfeld,<ref name=\"MbathaRawCrudup\" /> ''The Morning Show'''s head talent booker \n* [[N\u00e9stor Carbonell]] as Yanko Flores,<ref name=\"CarbonellDuplass\" /> ''The Morning Show'''s meteorologist\n* [[Karen Pittman]] as Mia Jordan,<ref name=\"PowleyPittmanTerry\" /> a producer at ''TMS''\n* [[Bel Powley]] as Claire Canway,<ref name=\"PowleyPittmanTerry\" /> a production assistant at ''TMS''\n* [[Desean Terry]] as Daniel Henderson,<ref name=\"PowleyPittmanTerry\" /> the co-host of ''TMS'''s weekend edition who has his sights set on the weekday host's chair\n* [[Jack Davenport]] as Jason Craig, Alex's husband from whom she is secretly separated\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Recurring===\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Tom Irwin (actor)|Tom Irwin]] as Fred Micklen, UBA's president <!-- (10 episodes) -->\n* Victoria Tate as Rena Robinson <!-- (10 episodes) -->\n* [[Janina Gavankar]] as Alison Namazi, Daniel's co-host on ''TMS'''s weekend edition <!-- (9 episodes) -->\n* [[Shari Belafonte]] as Julia <!-- (9 episodes) -->\n* [[Joe Marinelli]] as Donny Spagnoli <!-- (9 episodes) -->\n* Katherine Ko as Dhillon Reece-Smith <!-- (9 episodes) -->\n* [[Ian Gomez]] as Greg <!-- (8 episodes) -->\n* [[Augustus Prew]] as Sean <!-- (8 episodes) -->\n* Amber Friendly as Layla Bell <!-- (8 episodes) -->\n* Eli Bildner as Joel Rapkin <!-- (8 episodes) -->\n* [[Hannah Leder]] as Isabella <!-- (7 episodes) -->\n* [[Marcia Gay Harden]] as Maggie Brener <!-- (6 episodes) -->\n* [[Andrea Bendewald]] as Val\u00e9rie <!-- (6 episodes) -->\n* Michelle Meredith as Lindsey Sherman <!-- (6 episodes) -->\n* David Magidoff as Nicky Brooks <!-- (6 episodes) -->\n* Joe Pacheco as Bart Daley <!-- (6 episodes) -->\n* [[Kate Vernon]] as Geneva Micklen <!-- (5 episodes) -->\n* Oona Roche as Lizzy Craig <!-- (5 episodes) -->\n* [[Joe Tippett]] as Hal Jackson <!-- (4 episodes) -->\n* [[Roman Mitichyan]] as Sam Rudo <!-- (4 episodes) -->\n* [[Mindy Kaling]] as Audra <!-- (3 episodes) -->\n* [[Adina Porter]] as Sarah Graveler <!-- (3 episodes) -->\n* [[Brett Butler (actress)|Brett Butler]] as Sandy Jackson <!-- (3 episodes) -->\n* [[Philip Anthony-Rodriguez]] as Gabriel <!-- (3 episodes) -->\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Guest===\n====Season 1====\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Fred Melamed]] as Neal Altman <!-- (episodes 1, 3) -->\n* [[Ahna O'Reilly]] as Ashley Brown <!-- (episode 2, 4) -->\n* [[Natalia Warner]] as Cecily <!-- (episode 2, 4) -->\n* [[Mark Harelik]] as Richard <!-- (episode 3, 5) -->\n* [[Markus Flanagan]] as Gerald <!-- (episode 3, 5) -->\n* [[Embeth Davidtz]] as Paige Kessler <!-- (episode 1 & 8) -->\n* [[Martin Short]] as Dick Lundry <!-- (episode 3 & 8) -->\n* [[Andrew Leeds (actor)|Andrew Leeds]] as Alan <!-- (episode 1) -->\n* [[John Marshall Jones]] as Noah <!-- (episode 1) -->\n* [[Zuri Hall]] as Herself <!-- (episode 2) -->\n* [[Kelly Clarkson]] as Herself <!-- (episode 4) -->\n* [[Kelly Sullivan (actress)|Kelly Sullivan]] as Vicki Manderly <!-- (episode 4) -->\n* [[David Morse]] as Mr. Jackson <!-- (episode 5) -->\n* [[Julian Morris]] as Andrew <!-- (episode 5) -->\n* [[Cheyenne Jackson]] as Himself <!-- (episode 5) -->\n* [[Robert Cicchini]] as Robert <!-- (episode 5) -->\n* [[Mike O'Malley]] as Tim Eavers <!-- (episode 6) -->\n* [[Romy Rosemont]] as Sheila Lutkin <!-- (episode 7) -->\n* [[Brian Bowen Smith]] as Photographer <!-- (episode 7) -->\n* [[Paul Guilfoyle]] as Reid <!-- (episode 8) -->\n* [[Ethan Cohn]] as Jared <!-- (episode 8) -->\n* [[Dana Davis]] as Christine <!-- (episode 8) -->\n* [[Maria Sharapova]] as Herself <!-- (episode 9) -->\n* [[Hayes MacArthur]] as Marlon Tate <!-- (episode 10) -->\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Episodes==\n{{Series overview\n|released =y\n\n| color1     = f9d145\n| link1      = #Season 1 (2019)\n| episodes1  = 10\n| start1     = {{Start date|2019|11|1}}\n| end1       = {{End date|2019|12|20}}\n}}\n\n===Season 1 (2019)===\n{{Episode table |background=#f9d145 |overall= |title= |director= |writer= |airdate= |airdateR=<ref name=\"TFC\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/showatch/morning-show/listings/ |title=The Morning Show \u2013 Listings |website=[[The Futon Critic]] |access-date=October 12, 2019}}</ref> |released=y |episodes=\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 1\n |Title           = In the Dark Night of the Soul It\u2019s Always 3:30 in the Morning \n |DirectedBy      = [[Mimi Leder]]\n |WrittenBy       = [[Kerry Ehrin]] & [[Jay Carson]]\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|11|1}}\n |ShortSummary    = ''The Morning Show'', a popular news and talk morning television show, is thrown into chaos when co-anchor Mitch Kessler is fired amid allegations of sexual harassments. Fellow anchor Alex Levy grows furious at Mitch and the network for keeping her in the dark and later meets with Mitch, who reveals the network plans on replacing her. Elsewhere, conservative reporter Bradley Jackson becomes a viral sensation after a video of her angrily fact-checking a coal mine protester is posted on social media. Bradley quits following a confrontation with her boss and, after an argument with her family, is asked to appear on ''The Morning Show'' for an interview. Alex, who is skeptical about Bradley's claim that she was unaware of being filmed, presses her during the interview, which Bradley manages to get through. Network head Cory Ellison later calls Bradley and asks to meet her so they can discuss her future.\n |LineColor       = f9d145\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 2\n |Title           = A Seat at the Table\n |DirectedBy      = Mimi Leder\n |WrittenBy       = {{StoryTeleplay|s=Kerry Ehrin & Jay Carson|t=Kerry Ehrin}}\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|11|1}}\n |ShortSummary    = Cory arranges a meeting for Bradley with the show's executive producer, Chip Black. His dismissive manner sets Bradley off, leaving her sure she has ruined her opportunity. In the middle of contract negotiations and knowing the network needs her to stabilize the show after Mitch's departure, Alex tries to leverage the situation to get all of her demands, including co-host approval. Cory invites an unwitting Bradley to an event honoring Alex, and seats the women next to each other. Cory scoffs at Alex's demand for co-host approval, and calls her bluff when she threatens to leave the show. During her speech, Alex announces a shocked Bradley as her new co-host.\n |LineColor       = f9d145\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 3\n |Title           = Chaos is the New Cocaine\n |DirectedBy      = [[David Frankel]]\n |WrittenBy       = Erica Lipez\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|11|1}}\n |ShortSummary    = The staff of ''The Morning Show'' are in turmoil over the announcement. Alex has told the press that Bradley will debut the following Monday, so as the team prepares to work all weekend to prep her, Alex arrives to assert some control over the proceedings. Meanwhile, a frustrated Bradley has not even decided if she will accept the job. Chip asks Mia Jordan to be Bradley's producer, and announces her in the position before he has offered it to her. Forced to go along with Alex's announcement or lose face, network head Fred Micklen is furious, but Cory sees Bradley as an opportunity to reinvent the show and eventually be rid of Alex. Bradley is unhappy with her initial wardrobe and camera tests, so she challenges the copy Mia is providing her, and dispenses with the clothing chosen for her by Alex. Fred summons Alex to browbeat her in front of a room of network executives, but she informs him that he lost power over the show long ago, and from now on they will be doing things her way.\n |LineColor       = f9d145\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 4\n |Title           = That Woman\n |DirectedBy      = [[Lynn Shelton]]\n |WrittenBy       = Adam Milch\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|11|8}}\n |ShortSummary    = Bradley makes her debut on ''The Morning Show'' but, chafing at the scripted persona the show has given her, ends up mentioning her personal struggles as a teen, including having an abortion. This revelation incites controversy and infuriates Fred, but it also galvanizes the younger, pro-choice audience. Alex is convinced to give Bradley the interview with one of Mitch's accusers, but Bradley goes off script and the accuser reveals more than the producers had planned. Meanwhile, an investigation is launched by human resources into Mitch's conduct, with most of the crew offering their support to Mitch and denying knowledge of his sexual misconduct. Alex begins to experience some professional jealousy as America embraces Bradley and ratings rise.\n |LineColor       = f9d145\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 5\n |Title           = No One's Gonna Harm You, Not While I'm Around\n |DirectedBy      = David Frankel\n |WrittenBy       = Torrey Speer\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|11|15}}\n |ShortSummary    = ''The Morning Show'' braces itself for a story from ''[[The New York Times]]'' on Mitch's behavior leading him to crash the studio and beg his former coworkers to speak on the record in his defense. When the weekend hits Alex hosts a charity fundraiser which seemingly goes well and she is nevertheless thrown by talk of Bradley's success and Cory's proposal that they collaborate leading her to seek out solace from Mitch. Bradley tries to bond with her coworkers by going out to celebrate Claire's birthday at a bar only for the night to get heated as talk eventually turns to Mitch and Bradley receives a call from her estranged father. As the ''Times'' story hits, Mitch is enraged that Fred has thrown him under the bus and vows to take him down. \n |LineColor       = f9d145\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 6\n |Title           = The Pendulum Swings\n |DirectedBy      = [[Tucker Gates]]\n |WrittenBy       = Kristen Layden\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|11|22}}\n |ShortSummary    = ''The Morning Show'' travels to California to cover the wildfires engulfing the state. Alex struggles on and off screen as she is still angry at Bradley for accusing her of covering for Mitch and is devastated by Jason's decision to officially divorce. After melting down on screen she is comforted by Bradley and the two later reconcile when Alex opens up about the divorce and Bradley talks about her alcoholic father. Fearing for his job, Chip suggests he could be an ally in helping Cory take over from Fred leading Cory to suggest that he only come to him when he has real dirt on Fred. Hannah gives Claire professional advice which leads to Claire successfully lobbying Bradley for a position as her assistant. Later, Hannah catches her sneaking into Yanko's room to celebrate.  \n |LineColor       = f9d145\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 7\n |Title           = Open Waters\n |DirectedBy      = [[Roxann Dawson]]\n |WrittenBy       = Jeff Augustin\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|11|29}}\n |ShortSummary    = Alex and Jason announce to their daughter, Lizzy, that they are getting a divorce leading her to blame Alex for prioritizing her job over her family. Alex's PR team warns her that news of the divorce could damage her career causing her to lean on Bradley for support. Yanko and Claire are called to HR and decide to come clean about their relationship, a decision that relieves Yanko but leaves Claire wondering if her job is on the line. After an inappropriate remark about Mia leads to a member of the production team being fired by Chip, Mia has a meltdown and confirms to the entire studio that she was involved with Mitch. Bradley contemplates an offer from Mitch about interviewing him on air to reveal that the network was involved in covering for him. After he promises he can get a witness to corroborate his story he turns to Hannah, who he believes exchanged sexual favours for a promotion from him.\n |LineColor       = f9d145\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 8\n |Title           = Lonely at the Top\n |DirectedBy      = [[Michelle MacLaren]]\n |WrittenBy       = JC Lee\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|12|6}}\n |ShortSummary    = In 2017, Mitch stresses over turning 50. Now that his affair with Mia has recently ended, Mitch has Chip remove her from his team and place her with Alex, who the network is considering replacing due to tanking likability numbers. The cast and crew of ''The Morning Show'' surprise Mitch with a huge birthday party at the studio where Claire meets weatherman Yanko for the first time. As the party winds down Hannah begins to hear reports of the [[2017 Las Vegas shooting]] breaking over [[Twitter]]. Mitch and Alex travel to Vegas to cover the shooting with Mitch asking Chip to bring Hannah, still only a junior booker, along with the team. Alex and Mitch struggle emotionally with the reporting. When Mitch cannot sleep he heads out to a memorial and runs into Hannah. Taking her to his hotel room, Mitch assaults Hannah, who is shocked and freeze in the scene. Back in New York, Hannah barges into Fred's office who stops her before she can report the incident and promotes her to head booker to buy her silence.\n |LineColor       = f9d145\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 9\n |Title           = Play the Queen\n |DirectedBy      = [[Kevin Bray (director)|Kevin Bray]]\n |WrittenBy       = Erica Lipez & Ali Vingiano\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|12|13}}\n |ShortSummary    = Bradley reveals to Alex that she wants to go forward with interviewing Mitch in order to take down Fred. After Alex takes the news badly both women begin to work behind the scenes to get what they want with Bradley going to Cory for backing while Alex secretly approaches Fred to work out a plan for getting rid of Bradley. Hannah revealed to Claire that she was the one who reported them to HR, causing them to fall out and Claire loudly declaring her love for Yanko. The strain of public scrutiny, however, proves to be too much for Claire and she breaks up with him. Hannah confronts Mitch about how powerless she felt during their sexual encounter only for him to berate her for her naivet\u00e9. Hannah reluctantly agrees to corroborate how Fred enabled her promotion but anonymously. A heartbroken Chip who learned that Alex was willing to rid of him as part of a pact with Fred agrees to help Cory and Bradley in producing the Mitch interview.\n |LineColor       = f9d145\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 10\n |Title           = The Interview\n |DirectedBy      = Mimi Leder\n |WrittenBy       = Kerry Ehrin\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|12|20}}\n |ShortSummary    = After Mitch reveals that Hannah will corroborate his \"side of the story\", Bradley meets with Hannah. During this meeting, Hannah breaks down while trying to keep her composure. A reluctant Hannah tells Bradley to do whatever she'd like to do, just keep her anonymous seeing that UBA has offered her a producer job in Los Angeles. Aware that moves are being made behind the scenes expose his allowance of sexual misconduct, Fred grants Alex co-host approval in order to gain her support in firing Chip. Chip pressures Bradley to smuggle Mitch into ''The Morning Show'' to do the interview live and on air, letting her know that he has been fired and they need to act soon. Claire, trying to make amends with Hannah, shows up to her apartment and discovers that Hannah is dead from overdosing. News of her death shocks everyone, resulting in Bradley calling off the interview and a fight between Chip and Mitch. While on air, Alex snaps and along with Bradley, exposes Fred and UBA for their knowledge of sexual misconduct and creation of a toxic culture. The feed is cut off as Bradley encourages more people to speak out.\n|LineColor = f9d145\n}}\n}}\n\n==Production==\n===Development===\nOn November 8, 2017, it was announced that Apple had given the production a series order consisting of two seasons of ten episodes apiece. The series was set to be [[executive producer|executive produced]] by Jennifer Aniston, Reese Witherspoon, [[Jay Carson]], and Michael Ellenberg. Carson was expected to act as a writer and showrunner for the series as well. Production companies involved with the series were slated to consist of Media Res, [[Echo Films]], and [[Hello Sunshine (company)|Hello Sunshine]].<ref name=\"SeriesOrder\" /><ref name=\"SeriesOrder2\">{{Cite web |url=https://variety.com/2017/tv/news/apple-jennifer-aniston-reese-witherspoon-morning-shows-amazing-stories-1202610068/ |title=Apple Unveils Inaugural Scripted Series: Jennifer Aniston-Reese Witherspoon Morning TV Drama and 'Amazing Stories' |last=Littleton |first=Cynthia |date=November 8, 2017 |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |access-date=October 23, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"SeriesOrder3\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/jennifer-aniston-reese-witherspoon-morning-show-drama-lands-at-apple-2-season-order-1056144 |title=Jennifer Aniston, Reese Witherspoon Morning Show Drama Lands at Apple With Two-Season Order |last=Goldberg |first=Lesley |date=November 8, 2017 |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> On April 4, 2018, it was announced that Carson had departed the production over creative differences. He was expected to be replaced as executive producer and showrunner by [[Kerry Ehrin]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/apple-morning-show-jennifer-aniston-reese-witherspoon-kerry-ehrin-1202743257/ |title=Apple Sets Showrunner Shuffle on Morning Show Drama, Nabs Kerry Ehrin in Overall Deal |last=Littleton |first=Cynthia |date=April 3, 2018 |website=Variety |access-date=April 4, 2018}}</ref> On July 11, 2018, it was reported that [[Mimi Leder]] would serve as a director and executive producer for the series.<ref name=\"director\">{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/07/mimi-leder-to-direct-executive-produce-apples-morning-show-series-starring-reese-witherspoon-jennifer-aniston-1202424694/ |title=Mimi Leder To Direct & Executive Produce Apple's Morning Show Series Starring Reese Witherspoon & Jennifer Aniston |last=Andreeva |first=Nellie |date=July 11, 2018 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |access-date=July 11, 2018}}</ref> On October 23, 2018, it was reported that [[Kristin Hahn]] and Lauren Levy Neustadter would serve as additional executive producers for the series.<ref name=\"Carell\">{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/10/steve-carell-star-apple-morning-show-series-reese-witherspoon-jennifer-aniston-1202487958/ |title=Steve Carell To Star In Apple's Morning Show Series With Reese Witherspoon & Jennifer Aniston |last=Andreeva |first=Nellie |date=October 23, 2018 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |access-date=October 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe show cost $15 million per episode, with Aniston and Witherspoon each earning $2 million per episode, not including producing fees and ownership points.<ref>{{cite web |title= Inside Apple's Long, Bumpy Road to Hollywood |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/apples-bumpy-tv-launch-inside-tech-giants-impending-arrival-hollywood-1247577 |website= [[The Hollywood Reporter]] }}</ref>\n\n===Casting===\nAlongside the initial series announcement, it was confirmed that Aniston and Witherspoon had been cast in the series' lead roles.<ref name=\"SeriesOrder\" /><ref name=\"SeriesOrder2\" /><ref name=\"SeriesOrder3\" /> In October 2018, it was announced that [[Steve Carell]], [[Gugu Mbatha-Raw]], [[Billy Crudup]], [[N\u00e9stor Carbonell]] and [[Mark Duplass]] had been cast in series regular roles.<ref name=\"Carell\" /><ref name=\"MbathaRawCrudup\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/gugu-mbatha-raw-billy-crudup-join-apple-morning-show-drama-1154931 |title=Gugu Mbatha-Raw, Billy Crudup Join Apple Morning Show Drama |last=Goldberg |first=Lesley |date=October 25, 2018 |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |access-date=October 25, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"CarbonellDuplass\">{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/10/nestor-carbonell-mark-duplass-apple-morning-show-series-reese-witherspoon-jennifer-aniston-1202490050/ |title=Nestor Carbonell & Mark Duplass Join Apple's Morning Show Series |last=Petski |first=Denise |date=October 26, 2018 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |access-date=October 26, 2018}}</ref> On November 7, 2018, it was reported that [[Bel Powley]], [[Karen Pittman]], and [[Desean Terry]] had joined the main cast of the series.<ref name=\"PowleyPittmanTerry\">{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/11/apple-morning-show-series-bel-powley-karen-pittman-desean-terry-cast-1202497683/ |title=Bel Powley, Karen Pittman & Desean Terry Join Apple's Morning Show Series |last=Hipes |first=Patrick |date=November 7, 2018 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |access-date=November 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\nPrincipal photography for the first season commenced on October 31, 2018, at the [[James Oviatt Building]] in [[Los Angeles]], [[California]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.backstage.com/magazine/article/los-angeles-whats-filming-reese-witherspoon-jennifer-aniston-app-65820/ |title=L.A. What's Filming: Reese Witherspoon and Jennifer Aniston's 'The Morning Show' |last=Steves |first=Ashley |date=October 31, 2018 |website=[[Backstage (magazine)|Backstage]] |access-date=November 1, 2018}}</ref> Filming continued in Los Angeles until filming started in [[New York City]] on May 9, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://hollywoodlife.com/2019/05/08/reese-witherspoon-brunette-hair-makeover-the-morning-show/ |title=Reese Witherspoon Hair Makeover: Actress Goes Brunette On 'The Morning Show' Set \u2013 Before & After Pics |last=Charles |first=Marissa |date=2019-05-08 |website=Hollywood Life |language=en |access-date=2019-05-10}}</ref> Filming of the first season also wrapped in May 2019, after seven months of filming.<ref>{{Citation |last=TheEllenShow |title=Jennifer Aniston on Adam Sandler's Questionable Wardrobe |date=2019-06-05 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wNaZhbIOQQ8&t=274s |access-date=2019-06-26}}</ref>\n\nProduction on the second season began on February 24, 2020.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/11/the-morning-show-mimi-leder-hard-season-1-apple-tv-plus-1202186478/ |title=''The Morning Show'': Mimi Leder on a Demanding Season 1 Shoot \u2014 and Why She's Going Back For More |last=Travers |first=Ben |date=2019-11-03 |website=IndieWire |access-date=2019-11-03}}</ref> On March 12, 2020, Apple TV+ shut down production on the series due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/morning-show-shuts-down-production-due-coronavirus-concerns-1284295</ref>\n\n== Release ==\nAfter the [[Apple media events|Apple Special Event]] of March 25, 2019, Witherspoon announced on [[Instagram]] that the series would premiere in the fall of 2019.<ref name=\":0\" />  It premiered on [[Apple TV+]] on November 1, 2019.<ref name=\"SeriesOrder\">{{Cite web |url=http://deadline.com/2017/11/apple-reese-witherspoon-jennifer-aniston-morning-show-series-2-season-order-amazing-stories-reboot-1202204293/ |title=Apple Gives Reese Witherspoon-Jennifer Aniston Morning Show Series 2-Season Order, Confirms \u2018Amazing Stories\u2019 Reboot |last=Andreeva |first=Nellie |date=November 8, 2017 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.instagram.com/p/Bvctd5nDE0F/ |title=Reese Witherspoon on Instagram: \"So excited to announce my new @apple show at the #appleevent! It\u2019s called The Morning Show \u2600\ufe0fand it reveals what happens in the fast-paced\u2026\" |website=Instagram |access-date=2019-04-30}}</ref>\n\n=== Marketing ===\nDuring the Apple Special Event, a teaser trailer was released with footage from the series as well footage from other original series set to premiere on Apple TV+.<ref>{{Citation |last=Apple |title=Apple TV+ Preview \u2014 Coming Fall 2019 |date=2019-03-25 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Bt5k5Ix_wS8 |access-date=2019-05-11}}</ref> Furthermore, Aniston, Witherspoon, and Carell were at the event to tease the series.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://metro.co.uk/2019/03/25/jennifer-aniston-reese-witherspoon-tease-thrill-ride-apple-series-morning-show-9015516/ |title=Jennifer Aniston, Reese Witherspoon tease Apple's new series The Morning Show |date=2019-03-25 |website=Metro |language=en-US |access-date=2019-05-11}}</ref>\n\nOn August 12, 2019, Apple released a first look trailer for the series.<ref>{{Citation |title=The Morning Show \u2014 Official Teaser Trailer {{!}} Apple TV+ |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BeXtt2X6nDk |language=en |access-date=2019-08-12}}</ref> It was also revealed that the series will be titled ''Morning Wars'' in Australia, in order to distinguish the series from the [[The Morning Show (TV program)|Australian morning talk show of the same name]].<ref name=\"AU title\">{{Cite web |url=https://twitter.com/MacRumors/status/1160927411954946048/photo/1?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw%7Ctwcamp%5Etweetembed%7Ctwterm%5E1160927411954946048&ref_url=https://www.macrumors.com/ |title=Looks like \"The Morning Show\" will be called \"Morning Wars\" in Australia pic.twitter.com/LngIcFoRW3 |last=MacRumors.com |date=2019-08-12 |website=@MacRumors |language=en |access-date=2019-08-12}}</ref> On August 19, 2019, Apple released a full trailer for the series.<ref>{{Citation |title=The Morning Show \u2014 Official Trailer {{!}} Apple TV+ |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eA7D4_qU9jo |language=en |access-date=2019-08-19}}</ref>\n\n==Critical response==\nThe review aggregation website [[Rotten Tomatoes]] reported a 63% approval rating, based on 96 reviews, with an average rating of 5.66/10. The website's critical consensus reads, \"Flashy, but somewhat frivolous, ''The Morning Show'' often feels more like a vanity project than the hard-hitting drama it aspires to be\u2014but there is pleasure to be had in watching Jennifer Aniston and Reese Witherspoon give it their all.\"<ref>{{Cite web |title= The Morning Show: Season 1 (2019) |url= https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/the_morning_show/s01 |website= [[Rotten Tomatoes]] |access-date= December 24, 2019 }}</ref> [[Metacritic]], which uses a weighted average, assigned a score of 61 out of 100 based on reviews from 35 critics, indicating \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref>{{Cite web |title= The Morning Show: Season 1 |url= https://www.metacritic.com/tv/the-morning-show |website= [[Metacritic]] |access-date= December 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[Richard Roeper]] of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' gave a positive review and wrote: \"''The Morning Show'' doesn't have the cinematic gravitas of the [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]] series ''[[The Loudest Voice]]'' or the [[Aaron Sorkin]] poetry of [[HBO]]'s ''[[The Newsroom (American TV series)|The Newsroom]]''. It's more along the lines of the solid but underachieving ''[[Sports Night]]'' TV series from the late 1990s.\"<ref>{{cite web |date= 29 October 2019 |last= Roeper |first= Richard |author-link=Richard Roeper |title= Sex scandal a wakeup call for news team on AppleTV+\u2019s solid, starry new series ''The Morning Show'' |url= https://chicago.suntimes.com/2019/10/29/20938259/morning-show-review-appletv-apple-tv-plus-streaming-for-all-mankind-dickinson-jennifer-aniston |website= [[Chicago Sun-Times]] }}</ref>\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Award\n! Category\n! Recipient(s)\n! Result\n! {{